description: The Akademie für Psychotherapie & Interventionsforschung (API) at the University of Potsdam is a German training and treatment center for psychotherapy. It is the largest university training center in Germany for child and adolescent psychotherapy. Since 2014, they have also offered a shortened training program for psychological psychotherapists (PP). The API provides specialized training in group psychotherapy, relaxation techniques, treatment of families with problems in infancy and early childhood, learning therapy, and family law assessments, in addition to state-recognized training. The API's outpatient clinics and training practices treat approximately 1,200 children and adolescents annually, along with their caregivers. Their graduates consistently achieve top results in national examinations. The API collaborates with university hospitals in ten different federal states and with all clinics for child and adolescent psychiatry in Brandenburg and Berlin. They offer training programs for child and adolescent psychotherapists (KJP) and, since 2014, a shortened training program for psychological psychotherapists (PP) for certified KJPs with a psychological background. The API is the largest and most successful KJP training institute in Germany, with 514 graduates as of autumn 2024. The training focuses on practical experience in child and adolescent psychotherapy, with an emphasis on behavioral therapy. The API also offers a part-time postgraduate training program for child and adolescent psychotherapists to expand their treatment spectrum and knowledge, leading to certification as a psychological psychotherapist with a focus on behavioral therapy. The API's outpatient clinic addresses all relevant psychological issues in childhood and adolescence and treats mental disorders. Students of psychology, psychotherapy, and (social) pedagogy interested in training as child and adolescent psychotherapists can complete internships as part of their master's studies. The API is an accredited continuing education institute for psychotherapists specializing in psychotherapy for children and adolescents, using behavioral therapy, by the Ostdeutsche Psychotherapeutenkammer (OPK).
